Confidence is bred when you keep promises to yourself

That’s one of the many lessons I’ve learned in fitness.

When you have a ‘good’ lift, you walk out of the gym on a high

Your heart rate is up

You feel refreshed

and most of all, you feel proud.

However, not every day is a ‘good’ workout.

When I started experiencing ‘bad’ workouts, I still felt a huge sense of pride.

I used to think that sense of pride was from having a good workout.

Turns out that sense of pride came from having A workout.

Going whether I did or didn’t feel like it

I kept my word to myself and didn’t negotiate.

Showing up for what you know you need to do and keeping promises to yourself is what leads to confidence and self-esteem that can’t be bought. 
.

Who you are is more important than the how
.
without certain attributes, blue prints are useless
.
It took me a few years to realize this...
.
Spending money on workout plans that I wouldn’t stick to, and instead just do my own thing
.
Choose a workout split, only to “feel” bored with it a week or two later and change splits again
. 
It was a cycle that eventually led to me having to be honest..
.
Am I choosing the wrong plans, or am I not able to adhere to them long enough to see a result?
.
At this point in my life, I even believe you can be given the wrong blue print, but as long as you do it with intention & intensity you’ll eventually find your way to your result..
.
Just through grit.
.
#discipline #motivation #fitreels #motivational

Sometimes it looks like hitting the treadmill at 11:45pm at night while everyone else is asleep
.
Sometimes its waking up at 4am to hit the gym before a long day of travel
.
Sometimes its stuffing down a 1,000 calorie protein shake at the end of a long day to meet your caloric goal
.
None of these behaviors are normal or should be considered healthy, that’s up to you and your doctor to decide
.
But the days like this really are the determining factor in character development
.
If you’re someone that develops grit, or like @bedroskeuilian calls it...
.
Some FIO - Figure It Out
.
You welcome challenging days like this and actually look forward to them
.
Because on the other 99% of days when life is ‘normal’
.
When your schedule is predictable...
.
When you know what time you’ll be home..
.
When no hard deadlines are breathing down your neck...
.
No obstacles are in your way & you don’t get that phone call with bad news…
.
Being consistent becomes easy. 
.
Because you passed the test days where your schedule was working against you. Those days where it feels like a living, breathing thing trying to stop you from knocking off your check list for the day.
.
I know because I’ve been there & I still live through days where I feel like that.
.
But grit is the determining factor.
.
Again, this is not about neglecting sleep on a regular basis. To follow through on the examples in the beginning of this caption, you’ll need to go to bed earlier…
.
Which takes grit.
.
And this is not about being motivated and living like David Goggins.
.
Its about having my definition of Grit - knowing what needs to be done and doing it anyway despite the internal & external obstacles that get in your way.

This is the information age...everything you need to know is out there for taking.
.
Marketing in the fitness industry will try to tell you that there’s something you don’t know.
.
A special supplement
.
A fat burning tea
.
A special diet that will expedite your results
.
Its all nonsense.
.
Can some of these things give you encouragement and a little motivation, which can lead to results? Sure they can
.
However there is no magic product or 6 week plan that’s going to shed off weight and make it stay off forever.
.
Lasting, long term results take grit and consistency.
.
Not more information.
.
If information was the solution, everyone would look like a greek statue
.
You MIGHT find something that works quickly, but you’ll end up right back where you started
.
There are a lot of physiological and psychological reasons why it happens...
.
But I’ve seen it happen time and time again. Its as predictable as gravity.
.
Building real, long-lasting results is about grit, tenacity, building a program around your current lifestyle, job, family life...
.
In other words, things that take time & consistency
.
Its the harder path, and it doesn’t feel as good in the short term
.
But its the only way to truly change your life.
.
#fitness #fitreels #grit #exercise #diet #wellness #habits

.

.

.

.
But in reality, subtracting things out is what got me what I was looking for.

Fitness is a numbers game

And sometimes those numbers don't work in our favor

The numbers on the scale going up or down

Increasing the amount of weight we can lift in the gym

Increasing the amount of miles you can run within a certain amount of time

Sometimes we hit brick walls with these numbers.

Its the nature of the game

These brick walls can only be met with one thing - a change in the game plan.

Either 1 of 2 things are happening when you find yourself stuck with the numbers mentioned before

You're either haven't been following your game plan for long enough, or you've been doing it too long without making adjustments

Its more than likely the latter.

For example, if you're trying to lift heavier weights in the gym, and you've progressively been able to lift heavier weight each week for the past 6 weeks

But you find yourself stuck at the same weight for 3 weeks

You have to make adjustments for you to reach that next level

Maybe its upping your carbs or protein

or its changing the order in which you do certain exercises

or getting more sleep at night to allow for more recovery

Regardless, if a program works for you and gets you results, but you find yourself getting stuck after a while...

That means you need to up the intensity and/or make adjustments.

We can't do the same thing over and over again and expect a different result

Grit means staying persistent, but it also means doing things with intent and the smart way.
.
#grit #discipline #fitnessmotivation

What Cold Showers Taught Me About Mental Toughness
.
#coldshower #coldplunge #mindset

Everyone’s heard the saying about insanity
.
“Doing the same thing over and over again and expecting a different result”
.
A lot of fitness & living a healthy lifestyle is about sacrifice
.
Sacrificing old habits
.
Old substances
.
Old drinks that you used to consume daily (or a lot)
.
Giving up certain foods
.
A lot of people find themselves going back to these things more often than they would like, expecting themselves to feel okay with it
.
They usually rely on an article that says you can eat whatever you want and lose weight.
.
Or that habits they know they should be dropping is actually good for them in ‘moderation’
.
The reality is that you’re going to have to give up old vices & habits in order to level up
.
You can’t keep searching for happiness in the same place that took it away from you
.
There are some habits you can indulge occasionally, and do so guilt-free
.
Some things you may be called to give up forever if it really is that much of a problem
.
But if you’re expecting to let yourself completely off the hook once a week
.
You’re going to be disappointed
.
Your conscience knows what’s right.
.
Follow it.
.
#grit #discipline #mindset #motivation
